<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-638-909  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 638 909.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  Nov 7 1990 n145 p21(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IXI gives X.desktop boost with software initiative.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   IXI Ltd. (Marketing).andO;Product:   X.desktop (Graphical user interface) (Marketing)OSF/Motif (Graphical user interface) (Marketing).andO;Topic:     Software PublishersMarketing StrategyGraphical User InterfaceX Windows (Standard).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IXI gives X.desktop boost with software initiative The creator of X.desktop,IXI, has embarked on an X.desktop Software Initiative Program to makeapplications running under X.Window and OSF/Motif more useful.andM;Over 1 million users will be using X.desktop running with OSF/Motif andX.Window by the end of 1991, claims Ray Anderson, managing director of IXI.andM;&quot;IBM, Unisys, NCR, Dell and others have all standardised on X.desktop as anintegral part of their Unix graphical user interface,&quot; he says.andP;  &quot;It isimportant to get the software community organised to take advantage of thisgrowing audience.&quot;andM;The first phase of the initiative aims to make Unix applications amenable tothe mouse manipulations used in Macintosh-type interfaces by pre-configuringX.desktop.andM;Companies which have signed up include Ashton-Tate, Frame Technology,Informix, Ingres, Lotus, Oracle, Uniplex and WordPerfect.andM;Phase II, which Uniplex has already started, will involve changes in theapplications to communicate directly with X.desktop.andM;&quot;As Unix systems move over to the commercial desktop, visual userenvironments will become increasingly important.andP;  Oracle's Unix division iscurrently working to enhance the functionality of its products by supportingPhase II in early 1991,&quot; said James Sha, vice president of Oracle's Unixdivision.andO;</TEXT></DOC>